          "body": "The Sadducean high priesthood, filled with jealousy (*zēlos*, 5:17) at the apostolic momentum, performs a second arrest. The angel of the Lord empties the jail overnight (5:19) — not to extract the apostles to safety but to redeploy them at daybreak in the very temple courts from which they were arrested. The angel's commission — 'speak to the people the whole message of this Life' (5:20) — defines the gospel as *zōē*, life itself, the same theme John develops in his Gospel and First Epistle. Brought back before the Sanhedrin, Peter delivers the chapter's central declaration: 'We must obey God rather than men' (5:29). What follows in 5:30-32 is one of the most compressed kerygmatic statements in Acts: the God of the fathers raised Jesus whom you killed; God exalted Him as Prince and Savior; He grants repentance and forgiveness; we and the Spirit are joint witnesses."
